TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Comparative Advantage of Firms
AU  - Boehm, Johannes
AU  - Dhingra, Swati
AU  - Morrow, John
Y1  - 2022/04/28
PY  - 2022
DA  - 2022/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/720630
DO  - 10.1086/720630
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 3025
EP  - 3100
VL  - 130
IS  - 12
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Resource-based theories propose that firms grow by diversifying into products that use common capabilities. We provide evidence for common-input capabilities, using a policy that removed entry barriers in input markets to show that the similarity of a firm?s and an industry?s input mix determines firm production choices. We model industry choice and economies of scope from input capabilities. When the model is estimated for Indian manufacturing, input complementarities make firms 5% more likely to produce in an industry and are quantitatively as important as time-invariant drivers of coproduction rates. Upstream entry barriers were equivalent to a 9.5% tariff on inputs.
AB  - Resource-based theories propose that firms grow by diversifying into products that use common capabilities. We provide evidence for common-input capabilities, using a policy that removed entry barriers in input markets to show that the similarity of a firm?s and an industry?s input mix determines firm production choices. We model industry choice and economies of scope from input capabilities. When the model is estimated for Indian manufacturing, input complementarities make firms 5% more likely to produce in an industry and are quantitatively as important as time-invariant drivers of coproduction rates. Upstream entry barriers were equivalent to a 9.5% tariff on inputs.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/720630
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/720630
Y2  - 2024/03/20
